In [59]:
def get_emotion(whichemotion):
    if whichemotion.shape[0] == 1:
        indx = whichemotion[0]
    else:
        indx = np.argmax(whichemotion)
    if indx == 0:
        return 'angry'
    elif indx == 1:
        return 'disgust'
    elif indx == 2:
        return 'fear'
    elif indx == 3:
        return 'happy'
    elif indx == 4:
        return 'sad'
    elif indx == 5:
        return 'surprise'
    elif indx == 6:
        return 'neutral'

Dimensionality reduction is a technique used to reduce the number of features or variables in a dataset while preserving as much information as possible. It involves transforming a high-dimensional dataset into a lower-dimensional representation that retains the most important features of the original data.

Two main algorithms in dimentionlity reduction are:

  • Principle Component Analysis (PCA)
  • Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)

PCA¶

Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a commonly used unsupervised linear transformation technique. It reduces the number of dimensions by finding the maximum variance in high dimensional data. PCA reduces the number of dimensionality of the dataset.

We are going to converet the 3-d array happy_sad_train_X of dimension (28709, 48, 48) into a 2-d array happy_sad_2d of dimension (28709,2304), so that all the features of a same record is passed as a single array to the PCA transformation.

In [66]:
# Convert the array to 2-d
happy_sad_2d = happy_sad_train_X.reshape(happy_sad_train_X.shape[0], -1)
In [67]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

# Account for 99% of variance
pca_binary = PCA(0.99)
# Transformed image
image_transformed = pca_binary.fit_transform(happy_sad_2d)

print(f'{happy_sad_2d.shape[1]} features has been reduced to {image_transformed.shape[1]}')

2304 features has been reduced to 835

Variance refers to the amount of variability in a data set that can be attributed to each individual principal component. We have performed PCA on the 2-d array to account for 99% of variance, i.e the transformed image can represent the 99% of the information of the original data. We were able to capture 99% variance with 835 principal components or features.

We are going to display the difference between the PCA transformed data and the original data. To do that, we will inverse transform the PCA transformed 2-d array data. And then reshape the 2-d array to 3-d, so that it matches with the original data.

LDA¶

Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) is a supervised method that takes class labels into account when reducing the number of dimensions. The goal of LDA is to find a feature subspace that best optimizes class separability. In LDA it reduces the features to (number of classes - 1) features.

In our happy_sad_2d dataset, we have 2 classes:happy and sad. So LDA reduces the features to 1 feature(2-1).

In [70]:
from sklearn.discriminant_analysis import LinearDiscriminantAnalysis

# Perform LDA on the sampled dataset
lda = LinearDiscriminantAnalysis()
lda.fit(happy_sad_2d, happy_sad_train_y)
lda_transformed = lda.transform(happy_sad_2d)

print(f'{happy_sad_2d.shape[1]} features has been reduced to {lda_transformed.shape[1]}')

2304 features has been reduced to 1

As we have only one feature for a image, it will be hard to visualize and display the reduced features. Also it is hard to inverse the LDA transformed images.

We are going to use pinv function of numpy to inverse the LDA transformed image back to the original one. If the determinant of the array is zero it will not have an inverse and the inv function will not work. But pinv will. This is because pinv returns the inverse of the array when it is available and the pseudo inverse when it isn't. That is the reason for us to use pinv over inv function.

Using pinv function, we are going to get the approximate inverse for numerical data, eventhough it is not possible to inverse the image data.

In [71]:
from sklearn.utils.validation import check_is_fitted
from sklearn.utils import check_array, check_X_y

# Perform inverse transform on LDA 
def inverse_transform(lda, x):
    if lda.solver == 'lsqr':
        raise NotImplementedError("(inverse) transform not implemented for 'lsqr' "
                                  "solver (use 'svd' or 'eigen').")
    check_is_fitted(lda, ['xbar_', 'scalings_'], all_or_any=any)

    # Numpy's pinverse
    inv = np.linalg.pinv(lda.scalings_)

    x = check_array(x)
    # Perform operation based on the type of solver
    if lda.solver == 'svd':
        x_back = np.dot(x, inv) + lda.xbar_
    elif lda.solver == 'eigen':
        x_back = np.dot(x, inv)

    return x_back

In [76]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
from sklearn import metrics

# Visualize the model evaluation
def model_evaluation(pca_model, lda_model,test_pca_x,test_lda_x,happy_sad_test_y):
    # Predict on test set
    pca_prediction = pca_model.predict(test_pca_x)
    lda_prediction = lda_model.predict(test_lda_x)
    
    # Plot confusion matrix of PCA 
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    cmatrix_pca = confusion_matrix(happy_sad_test_y,pca_prediction)
    sns.heatmap(pd.DataFrame(cmatrix_pca,columns=['Happy','Sad'],index=['Happy','Sad']), annot=True, fmt='g')
    
    plt.ylabel('Actual label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.title('PCA model')
    
    # Plot confusion matrix of LDA
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    cmatrix_lda = confusion_matrix(happy_sad_test_y,lda_prediction)
    sns.heatmap(pd.DataFrame(cmatrix_lda,columns=['Happy','Sad'],index=['Happy','Sad']), annot=True, fmt='g')
    
    plt.ylabel('Actual label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.title('LDA model')
    
    # Calculate and print the accuracy
    print(f'Accuracy of the model trained with PCA is {metrics.accuracy_score(happy_sad_test_y, pca_prediction)*100:.2f}%')
    print(f'Accuracy of the model trained with LDA is {metrics.accuracy_score(happy_sad_test_y, lda_prediction)*100:.2f}%')

# Evaluate multi-label classification model
def model_multi_evaluation(pca_model, lda_model,test_pca_x,test_lda_x,test_y,label_order):
    pca_prediction = pca_model.predict(test_pca_x)
    lda_prediction = lda_model.predict(test_lda_x)
    
    # Plot the PCA model
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    cmatrix_pca = confusion_matrix(test_y,pca_prediction)
    sns.heatmap(pd.DataFrame(cmatrix_pca,columns=label_order,index=label_order), annot=True, fmt='g')
    
    plt.ylabel('Actual label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.title('PCA model')
    
    # Plot the LDA model
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    cmatrix_lda = confusion_matrix(test_y,lda_prediction)
    sns.heatmap(pd.DataFrame(cmatrix_lda,columns=label_order,index=label_order), annot=True, fmt='g')
    
    plt.ylabel('Actual label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.title('LDA model')
    
    # Calculate and print the accuracy
    print(f'Accuracy of the model trained with PCA is {metrics.accuracy_score(test_y, pca_prediction)*100:.2f}%')
    print(f'Accuracy of the model trained with LDA is {metrics.accuracy_score(test_y, lda_prediction)*100:.2f}%')

[4 Marks] f. Let's assume that some of the faces were labeled wrong in producing the dataset. Propose and implement a solution that identifies images that are potentially mislabeled. Show 10 samples based on the method you choose.

The k-nearest neighbors(KNN) algorithm, is a non-parametric, supervised learning classifier, which uses proximity to make classifications about the grouping of an individual data point. It is widely disposable in real-life scenarios since it does not make any underlying assumptions about the distribution of data.

We are going to train a model using KNN, and will be checking the probabilty of the record being certain label. The potential mislabels will be given away by finding and analyzing the noise probabilty.

In [107]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

def detect_noisy_samples(X,y,thres=.70): #Returns noisy indexes
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier().fit(X,y)
    # How much deviation the original label's probability has
    noise_prob = 1 - knn.predict_proba(X)[range(len(X)),y]
    return np.argwhere(noise_prob>thres).reshape(-1)
